ility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 10 December 2018 to Question 199449, what assessment his Department has made of whether the number of avoidable deaths of people with learning disabilities in the care of the NHS has reduced since the Care Quality Commission began working with NHS Improvement.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","202319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025301","Department for Education","false","2018-12-19","<p>The Department for Education has not assessed the educational outcomes of children and young people who have had a health diagnosis of pathological demand avoidance (PDA) as a distinct group.</p><p>The department collects data on the educational outcomes of children identified as having special educational needs in comparison to children without special needs. Where individual children and young people with PDA have been identified as having a special educational need, they will be captured via these data collections.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-12-19T17:03:21.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025301/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025301/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025301/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-14","Special Educational Needs: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment his Department has made of the educational outcomes for children with pathological demand avoidance.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","202296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025302","Department for Education","false","2018-12-19","<p>Children with complex special educational needs and disabilities (SEND) usually have an Education, Health and Care (EHC) plan. The SEND Code of Practice sets out the rights of parents and young people to request the school of their choice when a final EHC plan is issued.</p><p>Local authorities must name that school in the EHC plan unless it would not be suitable for the pupil’s age, ability, aptitude or SEND, or unless the attendance of the pupil there would be incompatible with the efficient education of others or the efficient use of resources. A school named in an EHC plan has a statutory duty to admit the child or young person.</p><p>Local authorities have a statutory duty to keep local provision for children and young people with SEND and their families under review to ensure that it continues to meet local needs. This would include the provision of sufficient school places that can support pupils with SEND.</p><p>The department has allocated £365 million of capital funding (over and above basic need funding) to help build new places at mainstream and special schools and to improve existing places to benefit current and future pupils. Local authorities must consult with local stakeholders to decide how best to spend their allocation.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-12-19T17:07:26.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025302/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025302/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025302/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-14","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he is taking to ensure that children with complex needs are able to obtain a place in a school appropriate for their needs.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","202297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025303","Department for Education","false","2018-12-19","<p>My right hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Education announced in a written ministerial statement on Monday 17 December that we will provide additional high needs funding to all local authorities, totalling £250 million over 2018-19 and 2019-20. This brings the total allocated for children and young people with more complex special educational needs and disabilities to £6.1 billion this year, up by over £1 billion from the £5 billion allocated in 2013. This additional investment will help to support local councils manage the increasing costs of provision for these pupils and students.</p><p>​We have also announced a further £100 million top-up to the Special Provision Capital Fund in 2019-20 to take our total investment to £365 million across 2018-21. This additional funding will give more children access to a good school or college place and pay for more state-of-the-art facilities, such as sensory rooms and specialist equipment.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-12-19T17:21:00.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025303/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025303/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025303/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-14","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department is taking to support local authorities which have seen a significant rise in the number of children with special educational needs.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","202298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025304","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-12-20","<p>The Department regularly assesses comparative levels of R&amp;D expenditure in the UK and EU member states.</p><p> </p><p>The latest ONS data estimates that overall gross R&amp;D expenditure in the UK was £33.1bn in 2016, which was 1.7% of GDP in that year. 2017 data is due to be released in March 2019. The latest OECD international comparison of R&amp;D expenditure ranked the UK 10th among EU nations in 2016. More details can be found here <a href="http://oe.cd/msti" target="_blank">http://oe.cd/msti</a>.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2018-12-20T10:58:58.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025304/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025304/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025304/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-12-14","Research: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what comparative assessment his Department has made of the level of research and development expenditure in the UK and EU member states.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","202309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025305","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-12-20","<p>The Department has no plans to produce and publish a formal review document or the evidence collected as part of it. In undertaking the review, the Department called for evidence from interested stakeholders which included several confidential individual case studies from organisations who have not permitted the Department to share these within the public domain. A summary of the findings will be shared with contributors to the review and we will continue to keep the impact of the regulations under close review, working closely with our stakeholders.</p><p> </p><p>National guidance is clear that National Health Service maternity treatment should always be considered as immediately necessary and provided to all patients regardless of whether or not they are entitled to receive it free of charge or there are doubts about whether they could pay if subsequently found to be chargeable under the regulations.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","202323 ; 202325","2018-12-20T17:30:23.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025305/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025305/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1025305/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-14","Health Services: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the Written Statement of 12 December 2018 on the review of amendments made to the NHS Overseas Visitor Charging Regulations in 2017, HLWS1142, if he will publish the full text of that review.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","202322"
